Content: The caterpillar's actions while building its cocoon support the idea that it is  —

A.Choice: too impatient to argue with the ant and the bee

Key.Rationale: The caterpillar's humble responses do not support the idea that it is too impatient to argue with the ant and the bee.

B.Choice: confused by the questions the ant and the bee are asking

Key.Rationale: The caterpillar's actions while building its cocoon do not support the idea that it is confused by the questions the ant and the bee are asking.

C.Choice: unconcerned about what the ant and the bee think about its house

Key.Rationale: The caterpillar's actions while building its cocoon support the idea that it is unconcerned about what the ant and the bee think about its house.

D.Choice: afraid to show the ant and the bee the best way to make a house

Key.Rationale: The caterpillar's actions while building its cocoon do not support the idea that it is afraid to show the ant and the bee the best way to make a house.

Content: Which sentence does the author use to suggest that the caterpillar has experienced an important change?

F.Choice: Up and down the caterpillar's head moved, weaving and weaving.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not suggest that the caterpillar has experienced an important change.

G.Choice: At last the veil grew so thick that you could only guess that the caterpillar might still be at work inside.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not suggest that the caterpillar has experienced an important change.

H.Choice: But the caterpillar did not die.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not suggest that the caterpillar has experienced an important change.

J.Choice: Many days and nights passed, and at last what had once been the caterpillar began to stir and wake.

Key.Rationale: The text indicates time has passed and “what had once been the caterpillar” has now experienced an important change.

Content: Which of the following is the best summary of paragraphs 1 through 9?

A.Choice: An ant and a bee see a caterpillar making a house. Both of them talk to the caterpillar while it works to finish its task the only way it knows how.

Key.Rationale: It is not a brief statement of the main details of paragraphs 1 through 9.

B.Choice: A caterpillar is making a house out of something like silk on a twig. The house is called a cocoon, and it takes a long time to make.

Key.Rationale: This brief statement lists details that are not included in paragraphs 1 through 9.

C.Choice: A caterpillar is making a house for itself. An ant and a bee suggest better places for the caterpillar to live, but the caterpillar continues with its task.

Key.Rationale: It is a brief statement of the main details of paragraphs 1 through 9.

D.Choice: An ant and a bee watch a caterpillar making a house. They think the caterpillar is having trouble, so they suggest different places for it to live.

Key.Rationale: It is not a brief statement of the main details of paragraphs 1 through 9.

Content: In paragraph 6, the word a͟b͟s͟u͟r͟d means  —

Key.Rationale: “Silly” is a synonym for the word “absurd.”
“Absurd” does not mean “messy.”
“Absurd” does not mean “difficult.”
“Absurd” does not mean “gloomy.”

Content: Which sentence from the story shows that the caterpillar is successful at building a good house for itself?

A.Choice: Every time the caterpillar's head moved, it left behind something that looked like a glistening thread of silk.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that the caterpillar is successful at building a good house for itself.

B.Choice: Through the veil you could still faintly see the caterpillar moving.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that the caterpillar is successful at building a good house for itself.

C.Choice: The bee came by that way again and stopped to look at the little house.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that the caterpillar is successful at building a good house for itself.

D.Choice: It was fast asleep in its little cocoon house, knowing not whether the sun shone or the rain beat down.

Key.Rationale: This sentence shows that the caterpillar is successful at building a good house for itself.

Content: The author includes sensory language and vivid details in paragraph 15 to illustrate how  —

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 15 does not illustrate how quickly moths can move.
The sensory language and vivid details in paragraph 15 illustrate how beautiful the caterpillar has become.
Paragraph 15 does not illustrate how strong a cocoon can be.

J.Choice: perfectly the caterpillar has built the cocoon

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 15 does not illustrate how perfectly the caterpillar has built the cocoon.

Content: How was Dahl's career at the oil company similar to his military career?

A.Choice: Both careers gave Dahl experience as a spy.

Key.Rationale: Both careers did not give Dahl experience as a spy.

B.Choice: Both careers put Dahl in dangerous situations.

Key.Rationale: Both careers did not put Dahl in dangerous situations.

C.Choice: Both careers required Dahl to have excellent writing skills.

Key.Rationale: There is no mention that both careers required excellent writing skills.

D.Choice: Both careers presented Dahl with opportunities to learn new skills.

Key.Rationale: Both careers presented Dahl with opportunities to learn new skills.

Content: In paragraph 5, the word e͟n͟d͟l͟e͟s͟s means  —

Key.Rationale: The word “endless” does not mean “nearing the end.”
The word “endless” does not mean “able to end.”
The suffix ­ less means “without.”
The word “endless” does not mean “after the end.”

Content: The author included the information about Dahl becoming a father to explain  —

A.Choice: what types of stories Dahl most enjoyed writing

Key.Rationale: Dahl becoming a father does not explain what types of stories Dahl enjoyed writing.

B.Choice: how Dahl's children helped him improve his stories

Key.Rationale: Dahl becoming a father does not explain how Dahl's children helped him improve his stories.

C.Choice: when Dahl decided to become a writer

Key.Rationale: Dahl becoming a father does not explain when Dahl decided to become a writer.

D.Choice: why Dahl was inspired to write children's literature

Key.Rationale: What began as bedtime stories for his daughters quickly became famous children's books.

Content: The photographs of two of Dahl's books after paragraph 3 are included most likely to  —

F.Choice: suggest that they were the first stories written by Dahl

Key.Rationale: The photographs do not suggest that the books were the first stories written by Dahl.

G.Choice: encourage the reader to buy the books that Dahl wrote for his daughters

Key.Rationale: The photographs do not encourage the reader to buy the books that Dahl wrote.

H.Choice: show which books Dahl wrote while he was a spy

Key.Rationale: The photographs do not show which books Dahl wrote while he was a spy.

J.Choice: show examples of Dahl's books that the reader may recognize

Key.Rationale: The photographs show examples of Dahl's books that the reader may recognize.

Content: The author organizes the selection by  —

A.Choice: listing Dahl's accomplishments as a writer

Key.Rationale: The author does not organize the selection by listing Dahl's accomplishments as a writer.

B.Choice: comparing Dahl's life as a fighter pilot to his life as a writer

Key.Rationale: The author does not organize the selection by comparing Dahl's life as a pilot to his life as a writer.

C.Choice: describing Dahl's life from his childhood through his adulthood

Key.Rationale: The author organizes the selection by describing Dahl's life from childhood through adulthood.

D.Choice: explaining how Dahl's job at the Shell Oil Company led to new discoveries

Key.Rationale: The author does not organize the selection by explaining how Dahl's job at the Shell Oil Company led to new discoveries.

Content: Which sentence from the selection best shows that Dahl was a daring person?

F.Choice: While Dahl may be best known as an author of famous children's books, he also had an interesting life unrelated to his writing.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that Dahl was a daring person.

G.Choice: Before he started writing, he traveled to other countries, flew fighter planes, and worked as a spy.

Key.Rationale: This sentence gives examples that Dahl was a daring person.

H.Choice: Dahl soon learned that Africa had many new things to see.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that Dahl was a daring person.

J.Choice: The mystery stories were quite popular.

Key.Rationale: This sentence does not show that Dahl was a daring person.

Content: What prevented Ricochet from becoming a service animal?

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 2 states that Ricochet liked to chase birds, which caused her to fail service dog training.

B.Choice: She had to get on a surfboard.

Key.Rationale: Getting on a surfboard was not a skill Ricochet needed to learn in order to become a service animal.

C.Choice: She had to learn how to open doors.

Key.Rationale: Learning how to open doors was not what prevented Ricochet from becoming a service animal.

D.Choice: She received too much attention from people.

Key.Rationale: Receiving attention from people did not prevent Ricochet from becoming a service animal.

Content: The author wrote this article most likely to  —

F.Choice: convince the reader to support the work that dogs do for others

Key.Rationale: The author did not write this article to convince the reader to support the work that dogs do for others.

G.Choice: inform the reader about the special work of an unusual dog

Key.Rationale: The author informs the reader about how one dog is using her special talents to raise funds that help both people and animals.

H.Choice: explain to the reader how a dog becomes a service animal

Key.Rationale: The author does not explain the process of how a dog becomes a service animal.

J.Choice: teach the reader how to train dogs to surf

Key.Rationale: The author does not teach the reader how to train dogs to surf.

Content: What information is included in the section titled “A Talented Fund-Raiser”?

A.Choice: Some of the causes that Ricochet has helped

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 6 lists some of the causes Ricochet has helped.

B.Choice: A description of how Ricochet learned to surf

Key.Rationale: Paragraphs 6 and 7 do not describe how Ricochet learned to surf.

C.Choice: An explanation of why Ricochet could not be a service dog

Key.Rationale: Paragraphs 6 and 7 do not explain why Ricochet could not be a service dog.

D.Choice: A story about the first time Ricochet surfed to raise money

Key.Rationale: Paragraphs 6 and 7 do not tell a story about the first time Ricochet surfed to raise money.

Content: What is the best summary of the article?

F.Choice: Ricochet can surf very well. She helps many people and animals who are in need. She has helped buy pet oxygen masks for fire departments. She has also helped raise money for teddy bears for children in hospitals and people in nursing homes.

Key.Rationale: This summary only lists a few details of some of the causes that Ricochet has helped.

G.Choice: Many people have watched Ricochet surf. The first time the dog surfed for a cause, she hopped on the back of a boy's surfboard. People were amazed. Because of this, they gave money for the boy to get his own service dog.

Key.Rationale: This summary addresses only one section of the article.

H.Choice: Ricochet helps people and animals by participating in fund-raising events. She helps out by surfing, even though she is a dog. The first person she helped was a boy named Patrick who had always dreamed of surfing even though he could not walk.

Key.Rationale: This summary addresses only the first time Ricochet surfed to raise money.

J.Choice: Ricochet was training to be a service dog but did not qualify. Instead, she learned to surf, and her trainer realized that she could help others with this unusual skill. Today, Ricochet surfs for an organization that raises money for different causes.

Key.Rationale: This summary is a brief statement of the main details of the article from beginning to end.

Content: Read the dictionary entry for the word c͟o͟m͟m͟o͟n.

:box:common \'kä-mən\ adjective
1. shared by people or groups
2. regularly seen or used
3. expected actions or behavior
4. not having wealth or privilege
Which definition best matches the way c͟o͟m͟m͟o͟n is used in paragraph 1?

Key.Rationale: Definition 1 does not match the way “common” is used in paragraph 1.
Definition 2 best matches the way “common” is used in paragraph 1.
Definition 3 does not match the way “common” is used in paragraph 1.
Definition 4 does not match the way “common” is used in paragraph 1.

Content: The reader can conclude that McDermott most likely  —

F.Choice: thinks horses are better guide animals than dogs

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence to support the conclusion that McDermott thinks horses are better guide animals than dogs.

G.Choice: enjoys helping others find guide animals to help them

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence to support the conclusion that McDermott helps others find guide animals.

H.Choice: believed Confetti needed more training to help Spencer

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence to support the conclusion that McDermott believed Confetti needed more training.

J.Choice: misses Confetti but is happy that the horse can help Spencer

Key.Rationale: The reader can conclude that McDermott misses Confetti but is happy that the horse can help Spencer.

Content: The author included paragraph 4 of the selection to  —

A.Choice: explain what Confetti does when she is not working

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 4 does not explain what Confetti does when she is not working.

B.Choice: demonstrate that Confetti is a friendly guide horse

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 4 does not demonstrate that Confetti is a friendly guide horse.

C.Choice: describe what Confetti's life is like with Spencer

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 4 describes what Confetti's life is like living with Spencer.

D.Choice: show that Confetti is able to take care of herself

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 4 does not show that Confetti is able to take care of herself.

Content: What is the main idea of the selection?

F.Choice: Spencer spent a long time trying to find a guide horse to help her.

Key.Rationale: There are not enough details to support this as the main idea.

G.Choice: Confetti is a miniature horse that has become a wonderful guide animal.

Key.Rationale: The title and the details in the selection support that Confetti has become a wonderful guide animal.

H.Choice: Guide horses must be trained before they can help people with special needs.

Key.Rationale: There are not enough details to support this as the main idea.

J.Choice: Confetti is a lot like a dog and can go anywhere a guide dog can go.

Key.Rationale: There are not enough details to support this as the main idea.

Content: One difference between Ricochet and Confetti is that Ricochet  —

A.Choice: helps a person with special needs

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti help a person with special needs.

B.Choice: has an owner who cares about her

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti have owners that care about them.

C.Choice: was unsuccessful at becoming a guide animal

Key.Rationale: Ricochet's “energetic activity” made her unfit at becoming a guide animal.

D.Choice: had to learn to do something before helping others

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti obtained their special skill by learning it first before helping others.

Content: Both selections express the importance of  —

Key.Rationale: Neither selection expresses the importance of making animals famous.
Although both animals made a new friend in the people they helped, it is not expressed as important in both selections.
Neither selection expresses the importance of teaching about animals.
The overall importance of both selections is caring for those with special needs.

Content: Which sentence best describes a difference between Ricochet and Confetti?

A.Choice: Ricochet required training, but Confetti did not.

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti did require special training in order to help others with special needs.

B.Choice: Ricochet helps many people, but Confetti helps one person.

Key.Rationale: Ricochet raises money for many causes that help both people and animals, while Confetti is a full- time guide for one person.

C.Choice: Ricochet spends time outdoors, but Confetti works indoors.

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti spend time outdoors helping people with special needs.

D.Choice: Ricochet does not notice other animals, but Confetti does.

Key.Rationale: Ricochet notices birds, which is why she could not be a service animal.

Content: What is one difference between the animals featured in the two selections?

F.Choice: Ricochet was able to stay with her owner, but Confetti had to leave her owner in order to do her job.

Key.Rationale: Ricochet was able to stay with her original owner, but Confetti had to leave her original owner in order to become a guide animal.

G.Choice: Ricochet's duties are typical for a service animal, but Confetti performs tasks that are not usually done by an animal.

Key.Rationale: Ricochet's talents are unusual, but Confetti performs the same tasks as a guide dog.

H.Choice: Ricochet's owner believed she would make a good guide animal, but Confetti's owner worried that she would not make a good guide animal.

Key.Rationale: There is no evidence to support that Confetti's owner worried that she would not make a good guide animal.

J.Choice: Ricochet must stay at home with her trainer, but Confetti travels as part of her job.

Key.Rationale: Both Ricochet and Confetti travel with their owners in order to help people with special needs.

Content: Read line 8 from the poem.
:box:Hurrylikethis
The lack of spaces between the words creates a sense of  —

Key.Rationale: The lack of spaces between the words does not create a sense of mystery.
The lack of spaces between the words creates a sense of feeling rushed.
The lack of spaces between the words does not create a sense of happiness.
The lack of spaces between the words does not create a sense of feeling surprised.

Content: What is the message of this poem?

F.Choice: Time moves at the same pace no matter what is happening.

Key.Rationale: The message of the poem is not about time moving at the same pace no matter what is happening.

G.Choice: Time seems to pass more quickly in the morning than in the evening.

Key.Rationale: The message of the poem is not about time passing more quickly in the morning than in the evening.

H.Choice: The passage of time is usually noticed more by older people than by younger people.

Key.Rationale: The message of the poem is not about the passage of time being noticed more by older people than younger people.

J.Choice: Time seems to pass at different speeds depending on what we are doing.

Key.Rationale: The message of the poem is time seems to pass at different speeds depending on what we are doing.

Content: How is line 21 important to the poem?

A.Choice: It shows that the speaker is confused.

Key.Rationale: Line 21 does not show that the speaker is confused.

B.Choice: It shows that the speaker has to leave.

Key.Rationale: Line 21 does not show that the speaker has to leave.

C.Choice: It suggests that the speaker is having fun.

Key.Rationale: Line 21 does not suggest that the speaker is having fun.

D.Choice: It uses a sound to describe the speaker's experience.

Key.Rationale: Line 21 uses a sound to describe the speaker's sense of time passing quickly.

Content: In line 1 of the poem, what does the word p͟e͟c͟u͟l͟i͟a͟r mean?

Key.Rationale: The word “peculiar” introduces the strangeness of time.
The word “peculiar” does not show how time is “certain.”
The word “peculiar” does not show how time is “sensible.”
The word “peculiar” does not show how time is “cautious.”

Content: Read line 12 from the poem.
:box:Notice how an hour crawls along and crawls along
Which of these does the poet use in line 12 to help the reader understand that time seems to pass slowly?

Key.Rationale: The repetition of “crawls along” helps the reader understand that time seems to pass slowly.
Line 12 is not an example of meter.
Line 12 is not an example of a line break.
Line 12 is not an example of rhyme.

Content: The first stanza is important to the poem because it  —

F.Choice: describes an experience the speaker enjoys

Key.Rationale: The first stanza does not describe an experience the speaker enjoys.

G.Choice: introduces the subject of the poem

Key.Rationale: The first stanza introduces time as the subject of the poem.

H.Choice: identifies the setting of the poem

Key.Rationale: The first stanza does not identify the setting of the poem.
The first stanza does not reveal the speaker's feelings.

Content: The photograph under paragraph 1 suggests that  —

A.Choice: artists who make papel picado need many years of training

Key.Rationale: The picture does not show the number of years artists train.

B.Choice: making papel picado is something that a person must do alone

Key.Rationale: The picture does not show a person working alone.

C.Choice: artists use detailed designs for papel picado

Key.Rationale: The picture shows the designs for papel picado.

D.Choice: making papel picado requires only a short amount of time to complete

Key.Rationale: The picture does not show the amount of time needed to make papel picado.

Content: Which sentence from the selection expresses an opinion?

F.Choice: Papel picado is a beautiful and delicate form of paper art.

Key.Rationale: The word beautiful is an opinion, which can not be proven.

G.Choice: In Spanish, papel means “paper,” and picado means “punched.”

Key.Rationale: This is a fact that can be proven to be true.

H.Choice: To make papel picado, artists first draw the pattern for the art.

Key.Rationale: This is a fact that can be proven to be true.

J.Choice: The artists then use sharp chisels to cut through the layers of tissue paper.

Key.Rationale: This is a fact that can be proven to be true.

Content: The author includes paragraph 6 most likely to  —

A.Choice: inform the reader of places where papel picado should not be displayed

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 6 does provide information where papel picado can be displayed.

B.Choice: describe different reasons that people like papel picado

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 6 does not provide reasons why people like papel picado.

C.Choice: tell the reader where to find the materials needed to create papel picado

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 6 does not tell where materials can be found for papel picado.

D.Choice: explain how a problem with papel picado has been solved

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 6 begins with the problem of preserving the art, and then explains how artists solved the problem.

Content: According to the section titled “An Easy Way to Make Your Own Papel Picado,” what should a person do just before unfolding the paper?

Key.Rationale: Unfolding the paper is in step 4 and putting glue on the paper is after step 4.
Unfolding the paper is in step 4 and using string is after step 4.
Unfolding the paper is in step 4 and cutting the paper is just before in step 3.
This section does not include drawing the design.

Content: Which sentence from the selection explains why artists first created papel picado?

A.Choice: People living in Mexico soon had a lot of this tissue paper, and they began using it to make decorations.

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 1 explains that people had a lot of the paper that made papel picado and that's why they began to create it.

B.Choice: They include images of people, animals, flowers, lettering, and any design that has special meaning to the artist.

Key.Rationale: It explains how the design looked and not why the artists created papel picado.

C.Choice: Stacking many sheets of paper allows the artists to create the same pattern on all the sheets at the same time.

Key.Rationale: It explains the same patterns used in papel picado but not why it was created.

D.Choice: On a papel picado wedding banner, for example, hearts and the names of the bride and groom may be part of the design.

Key.Rationale: It gives an example of how a wedding banner is designed and not why artists created papel picado.

Content: In which section would the reader find information about occasions where papel picado is often displayed?

Key.Rationale: This section tells the meaning of papel picado and not about when it is displayed.
This section tells how papel picado is made and not when it is displayed.

H.Choice: How Is Papel Picado Used Today?

Key.Rationale: Paragraph 5 provides examples of when papel picado is used such as holidays, birthdays, and other events.

J.Choice: An Easy Way to Make Your Own Papel Picado

Key.Rationale: This section gives directions on making papel picado and not when it is displayed.
